Dear Families,

    What fun we=E2=80=99ve had hearing your children=E2=80=99s news stories=
!  Today, during
Morning Meeting, we did a shared writing activity in which we worked
together to write a news story.  Our topic: signs of spring!

     (I added the picture post-Morning Meeting as many kids were concerned
that we=E2=80=99d lack an illustration to go with the text.)

     Shared writing is an opportunity for kids to collaborate, and puts
emphasis on composition (and leaves the transcribing to the teacher).
Especially as we launch a new unit on journalism/news writing, we want to
model this type of writing for kids.  Here is a little more about writing
and some information on building reading stamina:

Writing Wednesdays

      Our first Writing Wednesday seemed to go pretty smoothly.  We used
Zoom=E2=80=99s =E2=80=98Breakout Room=E2=80=99 feature to split into small =
groups for our twenty
minute synchronous writing session.  For some children, it seems to be an
encouraging and positive experience to see their peers writing along with
them.  A few kids, though, seemed a little stuck.  If your child is having
a difficult time writing during these sessions, they have a couple options:

   -

   Draw or sketch to plan their next news story
   -

   Add illustrations to an existing story
   -

   Draw or write in their idea notebook
   -

   Revise or edit an existing piece of writing

     Remember, for our purposes, anything can be a news story!  Kids have
been interested in sharing information they=E2=80=99ve learned about animal=
s-
that=E2=80=99s great!  They have also been writing about projects they are =
working
on- fantastic!  We want to continue the habit of writing a little bit each
day.

Reading Stamina and Independence in Reading

     A couple folks have asked about building independence/stamina in
reading.  Many children have reached a stage in their reading where they
can be taking more ownership of their reading; they are not stopping as
frequently to decode and are reading longer texts with more dialogue.

    In the classroom, our reading time is built into the daily schedule,
thus providing a solid block of time where the expectation is that kids a)
read independently, b) work with a teacher on a reading skill through
direct instruction, or c) read with a partner.  At home, we know this is
not necessarily the case, but there are a couple things families can do to
support independence and stamina as a =E2=80=9Cnext step=E2=80=9D in readin=
g.

Here are a couple thoughts:

   -

   Goal Setting: We worked to set reading goals at the beginning of the
   year, so children are familiar with this idea.
   -

      Reading goals can relate to the number of books or chapters read, or
      the number of minutes spent reading.
      -

      Reading goals can be daily or weekly.  Each day=E2=80=99s goal might =
be
      different (e.g., Tuesday and Thursday read for twenty minutes, but on
      Monday/Wednesday/Friday read for thirty-five minutes. Or you coud set=
 the
      goal to read for ninety minutes over the course of one week.)
      -

      Kids should be collaborators in setting their reading goals.  If they
      help set the goal, they will be more likely to stick to the plan.
      -

      Timers can work wonders.  I often set a timer in the classroom.  But
      I never answer the question of, =E2=80=9CHow many more minutes are le=
ft?=E2=80=9D
      -

      Write down your child=E2=80=99s goals.  They might enjoy a checklist =
or chart
      to motivate.
      -

      Talk about the idea of reading independence/stamina with your child
      as a =E2=80=9Cnext step=E2=80=9D in their reading.
      -

   Fluency: This is something many kids began working on in the classroom.
   Fluency includes expression, volume, pace, phrasing, and smoothness.  Th=
is
   is something that you can support when your child reads to you.  Fluency
   supports stamina as kids begin "scooping up" more and more words into
   phrases and reading with expression.  It helps kids to "get into the zon=
e"
   in reading.   Also, work on fluency can be done at a reading level sligh=
tly
   below what your child typically reads, as they are focusing their =E2=80=
=9Creading
   energy=E2=80=9D towards a new skill.  There are some prompts you might u=
se as you
   listen to your child read:
   -

      "Read it like the character."
      -

      "Reread that part and smooth out your voice."
      -

      "Look for punctuation to help you know how to say that part."
      -

      =E2=80=9CWhat does your voice do when you see a period?  Question mar=
k?
      Exclamation mark?  Bold print?=E2=80=9D
      -

      =E2=80=9CListen to me read, then echo the way I did it.=E2=80=9D
      -

   Reading Routines:
   -

      Some children find it helpful to go to a particular place to read (a
      cozy corner, chair, or fort).  Sometimes a reading light or special
      bookmark can help reading time feel a little more special.
      -

      Take breaks or =E2=80=9Ctag team=E2=80=9D reading to build up the dur=
ation of time
      spent reading
      -

      Many things can =E2=80=9Ccount=E2=80=9D as reading.  Graphic novels, =
audiobooks, and
      magazines are just fine!
      -

      Re-reading old favorites is a great way for kids to work towards
      fluency and building confidence.


Attached to this email are a couple charts to support reading fluency and
goal-setting.

